04517nam a22006615i 9781477303566DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211991txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773035667 a10.7560/7078182doi  a(DE-B1597)587358  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a327.810471 aHilton, Stanley E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBrazil and the Soviet Challenge, 1917–1947 /cStanley E. Hilton. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1991  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Challenge and Response (1917-1930) -- t2. The Debate over Trade and Recognition (1930-1934) -- t3. Red Rebellion (1935) -- t4. Toward the National Security State (1935-1937) -- t5. The Battle on the External Front (1935-1937) -- t6. Coming of the Estado Novo (1937) -- t7. Dictatorship, War, and Internal Security (1937-1941) -- t8. Global Conflict and Rapprochement (1941-1945) -- t9. Cold War Antagonisms (1945-1947) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1918 and 1961, Brazil and the USSR maintained formal diplomatic ties for only thirty-one months, at the end of World War II. Yet, despite the official distance, the USSR is the only external actor whose behavior, real or imagined, influenced the structure of the Brazilian state in the twentieth century. In Brazil and the Soviet Challenge, 1917–1947, Stanley Hilton provides the first analysis in any language of Brazilian policy toward the Soviet Union during this period. Drawing on American, British, and German diplomatic archives and unprecedented access to official and private Brazilian records, Hilton elucidates the connection between the Brazilian elite’s perception of a communist threat and the creation of the authoritarian Estado Novo (1937–1945), the forerunner of the post-1964 national security state. He shows how the 1935 communist revolt, prepared by Comintern agents, was a pivotal event in Brazilian history, making prophets of conservative alarmists and generating irresistible pressure for an authoritarian government to contain the Soviet threat. He details the Brazilian government’s secret cooperation with the Gestapo during the 1930s and its concomitant efforts to forge an anti-Soviet front in the Southern Cone. And he uncovers an unexplored aspect of Brazil’s national security policy, namely, the attempt to build counterintelligence capabilities not only within Brazil but also in neighboring countries. While the history of the Brazilian communist movement has been extensively studied, this is the first work to explore how images of the Soviet Union and its policies influenced the Brazilian foreign policy elite. It will be important reading for all students of twentieth-century political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBrazil-Foreign relations-Soviet Union. 0aBrazil-Politics and government-1889-1930. 0aBrazil-Politics and government-1930-1945. 0aBrazil-Politics and government-1945-1954. 0aNational security-Brazil. 0aPoliticians-Brazil-Attitudes. 0aSoviet Union-Foreign relations-Brazil. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477303566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477303566/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK